        <div class="col-md-9 nohighlight member-container">
            <h2 class="memberLink col-md-9" id="member-link-d0f3ebce-c7dc-453c-a472-5a2cd53da5af">
                Mr. Churchill
            </h2>
        </div>
            <div class="col-md-3 hidden-sm hidden-xs right-column ">
            <a href="#contribution-d0f3ebce-c7dc-453c-a472-5a2cd53da5af" rel="popover" class="link-to-contribution link-text" title="Share this contribution" data-placement="top"
               data-hop-url-shorten-url="/UrlShortener/ShorternUrl"
               data-hop-popover="http://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/1939-10-04/debates/0b75ca53-7646-4bed-b22a-6bccd726e8ab/RecruitmentAndPromotion#contribution-d0f3ebce-c7dc-453c-a472-5a2cd53da5af">
                <div class="share-icon">&nbsp;</div><span class="share-text">Share</span>
            </a>
        </div>

    


    <div class="inner">
        <div class="col-md-9 contribution content-container">



<p class="">I am naturally dealing with war time promotions at the moment, but we have to deal with the regular services of the Royal Navy, and I do not <span id="1944" class="column-number" data-column-number="1944"></span> propose for a moment that the 75 should be the maximum. I intend it to be the minimum, but, of course, we have to consider the number of officers who will be on our staff after the war is over.</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
                        <a href="#contribution-d0f3ebce-c7dc-453c-a472-5a2cd53da5af" rel="popover" class="link-to-contribution link-to-contribution-mobile link-text" title="Share this contribution" data-placement="top"
                           data-hop-url-shorten-url="/UrlShortener/ShorternUrl"
